|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/328918175|journal=International Academic Journal of Development Research|volume=5|issue=1|pages=128\u2013130|ref=CITEREFYildirim2017|via=}}\n\n=== Cited web sources ===\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Ashurbanipal|title=Ashurbanipal|last=|first=|date=|website=Encyclopaedia Britannica|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 November 2019|ref=CITEREFEncyclopaedia_Britannica}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancient.eu/Ashurbanipal/|title=Ashurbanipal|last=Mark|first=Joshua J.|date=2009|website=Ancient History Encyclopedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 November 2019|ref=CITEREFMark2009}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/nahum/3-18.htm|title=Nahum 3:18|last=|first=|date=|website=Bible Hub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 February 2020|ref=CITEREFNahum 3:18}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/sargon/essentials/diplomats/royalmarriage/|title=Royal marriage alliances and noble hostages|last=Radner|first=Karen|date=2013|website=Assyrian empire builders|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 November 2019|ref=CITEREFRadner2013}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [[Daniel David Luckenbill]]'s ''[https://oi.uchicago.edu/research/publications/misc/ancient-records-assyria-and-babylonia-volume-2-historical-records-assyria Ancient Records of Assyria and Babylonia Volume 2: Historical Records of Assyria From Sargon to the End]'', containing translations of Sinsharishkun's inscriptions.\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[Sargonid dynasty]]|||August|612 BC}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = [[Ashur-etil-ilani]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[King of Assyria]]\n| years = 627{{snd}}612 BC\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Ashur-uballit II]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n\n{{Assyrian kings}}\n{{Neo-Assyrian empire topics}}\n[[Category:Sargonid dynasty]]\n[[Category:7th-century BC Assyrian kings]]\n[[Category:Assyrian kings]]\n[[Category:612 BC deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:7th-century BC rulers in Asia]]\n[[Category:Kings of the Universe]]\n", "name_user": "Ichthyovenator", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRise to the throne and revolt of Sin-shumu-lishir", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sinsharishkun"}
{"title_page": "Rajat Chaudhuri", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian novelist and short story writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{orphan|date=February 2015}}\n\n'''Rajat Chaudhuri''' is an Indian novelist and short story writer. He is the author of the critically acclaimed works ''Hotel Calcutta'' (2013), a short story cycle; ''The Butterfly Effect'' (2018), the novel ''Amber Dusk'' (2007) and other books.<ref>\"[http://www.asianreviewofbooks.com/new/?ID=1517 Review of Hotel Calcutta at Asian Review of Books, 27 July 2013]\". Retrieved 20 September 2014.</ref><ref>\"[https://scroll.in/article/906022/how-horribly-wrong-can-experiments-in-science-go-this-novel-of-ideas-explores-the-possibilities Review of The Butterfly Effect in Scroll]\". Retrieved 10 May 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/23340549?uid=3738256&uid=2&uid=4&sid=21104469196841 Review of Amber Dusk, Indian Literature journal, Vol 52, No.3, Sahitya Akademi]\", Sahitya Akademi. Retrieved 20 September 2014.</ref> He is also a book reviewer and literary critic, reviewing for such publications as ''[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]]'', [[CNN-IBN]]Live, ''[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]'' (published by [[Sahitya Akademi]], India's National Academy of Letters) and ''The Asian Review of Books''.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nRajat Chaudhuri grew up and lives in [[Kolkata]]. He attended school at [[Ramakrishna Mission Vidyalaya, Narendrapur|Ramakrishna Mission Vidyalaya]] and studied Economics at [[University of Calcutta]]. \n\n==Career==\nHe is a bilingual writer writing in English and Bengali. His books include the novel ''Amber Dusk'' (2007), the short story cycle ''Hotel Calcutta'' (2013), and ''Calculus'' (2014), a collection of Bengali short stories. \n\nHe is the Charles Wallace Creative Writing Fellow (2014) of the University of Chichester, United Kingdom, Hawthornden Castle Fellow, Scotland, United Kingdom, and a past of Fellow of Sangam House International Writers\u2019 Residency (2010), India.<ref>\"[http://www.chi.ac.uk/department-english-and-creative-writing/charles-wallace-india-trust-fellowship-creative-writing Charles Wallace India Trust Fellowship in Creative Writing at University of Chichester] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104145324/http://www.chi.ac.uk/department-english-and-creative-writing/charles-wallace-india-trust-fellowship-creative-writing |date=4 November 2014 }}\". Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://webzineold.arko.or.kr/?MID=boardInfo&IDX=4&IDX2=900 Profile and report at Arts Council Korea (ARKO) webzine, Nov 2013]\". Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.sangamhouse.org/rajat-chaudhuri/ Profile at Sangam House]\". Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref> He is a Korean Arts Council-InKo sponsored resident writer (2013) of Toji Cultural Centre, which was set up by acclaimed Korean novelist [[Park Kyung-ni]].\n\nHis fiction, criticism and essays have appeared in publications including ''Indian Literature'' (Sahitya Akademi), ''Asian Review of Books'' (Hong Kong), ''American Book Review'' (University of Houston-Victoria),<ref>\" [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/american_book_review/toc/abr.36.6.html Chitpur Local and the Rip Van Winkles of Calcutta. Volume 36, Number 6, September/October 2015, pp. 7-23].\" DOI [http://10.1353/abr.2015.0117 10.1353/abr.2015.0117]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved 2 April 2016.</ref> ''Thresholds'' (University of Chichester),<ref>\"[http://blogs.chi.ac.uk/shortstoryforum/three-stories-about-love/ \"Three Stories of Love\", ''Thresholds'', University of Chichester, 2015]\". Retrieved December 2015</ref> ''Eclectica'', and ''Outlook magazine''.\n\nChaudhuri has been directly involved with environment and development related activism and has contributed to the United Nations Development Programme's Human Development Report.<ref>\"[http://hdr.undp.org/sites/default/files/reports/259/hdr_1998_en_complete_nostats.pdf UNDP Human Development Report 1998]\", United Nations Development Programme. Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref> He lobbies for and supports environment related causes. \n\nHe has worked for and nurtured development, environment and consumer rights groups, and has spoken about environment and sustainable consumption issues in venues within and outside the country. He has published books and monographs on such topics as the right to water, sustainable consumption, and green advertisements.<ref>\"[http://www.worldcat.org/title/water-what-are-our-rights-to-it/oclc/609012412 Water: What are our Rights to it?]\"  Water: What are our Rights to it? Retrieved 10 October 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.worldcat.org/title/green-advertisements-are-they-telling-the-truth/oclc/588502226 Green Advertisements \u2013 Are they Telling the Truth?]\" Green Advertisements \u2013 Are they Telling the Truth? Retrieved 10 October 2014.</ref> \n\nChaudhuri has also served as the developing country (Southern) coordinator on the United Nations [[Commission on Sustainable Development]] (UNCSD) NGO caucus for climate change and energy.<ref>\"[http://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/content/documents/1623MG%20guidelines.pdf Guidelines for Major Groups on CSD 9]\". Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref> He has appeared in environment, science fiction and international cultural meetings and communication fora like Escape Velocity organised by [[Museum of Science Fiction]] in Washington D.C., [[International Communication Association]] (ICA) events and other places speaking about biotechnology in fiction, sustainability narratives and allied issues while doing readings from his books.<ref>[https://escapevelocity2019.sched.com/speaker/rajat_chaudhuri.jumxyz98 Rajat Chaudhuri, Escape Velocity 2019]\", Retrieved 06 June 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.rajatchaudhuri.net/p/blog-page.html Rajat Chaudhuri, The Butterfly Effect]\", Retrieved 06 June 2019.</ref>    \n\n=== ''The Butterfly Effect'' ===\nAt the centre of a near-future, post-apocalyptic Darkland is the chaotic city of Calcutta. Here Captain Old, a retired policeman who is also a hired assassin receives news that could help unravel the roots of a scourge that has devastated the continent. But problems begin to pile up for him till his own life is at stake. In another narrative we find a group of Indian tourists disappearing in Korea and a detective arriving in Seoul to investigate. But soon the private eye is overwhelmed by incidents that is far beyond his ken as a crime investigator. \n\nMeanwhile in England there is a hotshot geneticist working away on a secret project which he believes could change the world. Each of these distinct but interconnected narratives, arranged in a Russian doll<ref>\"[https://scroll.in/article/892151/this-timely-novel-explores-a-dystopian-asian-future-the-result-of-interference-with-nature/ Book Ecerpt,Scroll.in]\", Retrieved 29 September 2018.</ref> structure, mingle with each other as we near the resolution of this work of speculative fiction which balances science, spirituality and a gentle way of life. This novel has been compared to [[Philip K. Dick]]'s [[Blade Runner]] (based on Dick's 1968 novel [[Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?]]) for its dystopian settings.<ref>\"[https://www-outlookindia-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.outlookindia.com/magazine/amp/books-calcutta-in-dark-sci/301138?usqp=mq331AQCCAE%3D&amp_js_v=0.1#aoh=15507883077220&csi=1&referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.outlookindia.com%2Fmagazine%2Fstory%2Fbooks-calcutta-in-dark-sci%2F301138/ Calcutta in Dark Sci in Outlook Magazine, February 2019]\", Retrieved 02 March 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.consumingcyberpunk.com/blog/2019/1/7/chasing-the-moment-in-the-butterfly-effect/ Chasing the Moment in the Butterfly Effect, Consuming Cyberpunk, January 2019]\", Retrieved 27 February 2019.</ref> This book has been listed by Book Riot community as one of \"50 must-read novels about eco-disaster\".<ref>\"[https://bookriot.com/2019/04/22/novels-about-eco-disasters/ 50 Must Read Novels about Eco-Disaster, Book Riot, April 2019]\", Retrieved 06 June 2019.</ref>\n\n=== ''Calcutta Nights'' ===\nTranslated work of narrative nonfiction originally written in Bengali (titled Raater Kolkata) by author [[Hemendra Kumar Roy]] in the year 1923. Translated into English by Rajat Chaudhuri, Calcutta Nights is the real-life account of the night-time wanderings of author Hemendra Kumar Roy in the forbidden, dangerous and exciting places of the city of [[Calcutta]].<ref>\"[https://www.dailypioneer.com/2020/sunday-edition/babus--bordellos--and-gaslit-nights.html/ Babus, Bordellos, and Gaslit Nights, The Pioneer, 12 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref><ref>\"[https://scroll.in/article/948962/calcuttas-ladies-of-the-night-a-forgotten-bengali-classic-offers-a-glimpse-of-a-racy-lifestyle/ Calcutta\u2019s ladies of the night: A forgotten Bengali classic offers a glimpse of a racy lifestyle, Scroll.in, 07 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/book-reveals-kolkatas-best-kept-secrets/1720549/ Book reveals Kolkata\u2019s best kept secrets, Outlook, 29 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref> The chapters in the book cover the brothels of Calcutta's red-light district, the dens of hoodlums, the crematoriums, night-time theatres, beggars hovels, festive streets, the `white town' area of Esplanade, hotels among others. The book according to reports `reveals Calcutta's best kept secrets' and acts like a `guidebook to the dark dens of eeriness' of the city of Calcutta.<ref>\"[https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/book-reveals-kolkatas-best-kept-secrets/1720549/ Book reveals Kolkata\u2019s best kept secrets, Outlook, 29 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/2020/jan/19/from-the-written-world-books-to-look-out-for-in-2020-2091352.html/ From the written world: Books to look out for in 2020, The New Indian Express, 19 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref>[[The South China Morning Post]] in its review, described this book as `a 1920s tour through the seedy nightlife of Calcutta in this tale of beauty and decadence'.<ref>\"[https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/arts-culture/article/3074195/sex-and-city-1920s-tour-through-seedy-nightlife-calcutta/ Sex and the city: a 1920s tour through the seedy nightlife of Calcutta in this tale of beauty and decadence, South China Morning Post,  09 March 2020]\", Retrieved 15 April 2020.</ref>\n\n=== ''Hotel Calcutta'' ===\nAn old Calcutta hotel is under the threat of demolition from land sharks  who want to replace it with a shopping mall. At this time a monk appears and prophesies that the hotel can be saved if people tell stories within its four walls every day. Thus begins a chain of storytelling by guests and hotel staff which brings together  realistic and speculative storytelling traditions. The frame story of the hotel's possible demolition flows parallelly till in the final pages there is an unexpected resolution. This book has been mentioned by critics for its evocative descriptions and the magic of storytelling.<ref>\"[http://www.thethumbprintmag.com/the-magic-of-storytelling/ The Magic of Storytelling, Anu Kumar, The Thumb Print Magazine]\",  Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref>\n\n=== ''Amber Dusk'' ===\n''Amber Dusk'' is a cross-cultural novel set in Calcutta and Paris amidst the rapid economic changes of a newly liberalised India. The young Rishi, in love with the French photographer Valence, travels west for work. Meanwhile, his friend, the hard nosed Pedro Braganza, looking for the good life, is taking too many chances in Calcutta. \n\nWhile in Paris, Rishi gets drawn into a vortex of racism and sporadic violence unleashed on the city by a little known neo-Nazi white supremacist outfit. Pedro has been putting in place his get-rich-quick plans and the initial success goes to his head. Then something happens which puts the two friends on a collision course against each other. It will be difficult for both of them to come out of it unscathed.\n\nThe novel was welcomed by critics for exploring surrealistic themes and for its handling of cross-cultural themes.<ref>\"[http://archive.deccanherald.com/content/Feb32008/books2008020250107.asp Surreal Explored, Deccan Herald, 3rd Feb, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105234605/http://archive.deccanherald.com/content/Feb32008/books2008020250107.asp |date=2014-11-05 }}\", Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref>\n\n=== ''The Best Asian Speculative Fiction'' ===\n\nAn edited anthology of speculative stories from all over Asia selected, edited and introduced by Rajat Chaudhuri, the book covers science fiction, fantasy, horror, weird and other sub-genres of speculative fiction from authors in more than a dozen Asian countries. \n\nThe book has been described as \"one of the most comprehensive speculative fiction collection from the continent.\"<ref>[https://www.singaporewritersfestival.com/nacswf/nacswf/programme-listing/free-events/The-Best-Asian-Short-Stories-2018.html Singapore Writers Festival] Retrieved 19 December 2018.</ref> The critic for The Telegraph describes this book of stories as being at \"the brink of a strange new world\" and as a \"necessary and successful conglomerate.\"<ref>[https://epaper.telegraphindia.com/imageview_266596_15412744_4_71_26-04-2019_15_i_1_sf.html The Telegraph, India] Retrieved 6 June 2019.</ref> The literary commentator Agnes S. K. Yeow  writing in Southeast Asian Review of English (SARE)<ref>[https://sare.um.edu.my/article/view/21090/10727 Yeow, Agnes S.K. (October 30, 2009). Book review in Southeast Asian Review of English (SARE), Universiti Malaya, Vol 56, Issue 2, 2019.] Accessed December 26, 2019.</ref> has described the book as `An important contribution to an ever-expanding and dynamic literary form'.\n\n=== ''Calculus'' ===\n''Calculus'' is a collection of short fiction written in Bengali. Set in the city of Calcutta and its outskirts these stories bring together characters like autorickshaw drivers who speak a dead language, tantric practitioners with secret agendas, occult detectives and more which finally portray hidden facets of the city and its people.  \n\nCritics have described the stories as postmodernist and magical, with one critic saying the book \"transports us to a symbolic plane of existence, perched between the possible and the impossible.\"<ref>[http://ekakmatra2013.blogspot.in/2016/02/blog-post.html Politics peley oboshyoi porben. (in Bengali) Book review of Calculus in Ekak Matra, February 2016.] Retrieved 6 March 2016.</ref>\n\n== Fellowships and awards ==\n* Hawthornden Fellow, Scotland, UK, 2015<ref>[http://kitaab.org/2015/07/24/demons-at-a-calcutta-playhouse-kitaab-review-of-the-firebird-by-saikat-majumdar/ Hawthornden Fellow, Scotland, UK, 2015]</ref>\n* Charles Wallace Creative Writing Fellow<ref>[http://www.britishcouncil.in/study-uk/scholarships/charles-wallace-trust/visiting-fellows Charles Wallace Creative Writing Fellow]</ref> at University of Chichester, United Kingdom, 2014\n* Arts Council Korea<ref>[http://webzineold.arko.or.kr/?MID=boardInfo&IDX=4&IDX2=900 Arts Council Korea]</ref> and InKo Fellow<ref>[http://www.inkocentre.org/Indian_writer_at_Writing_Residency.html InKo Fellow]</ref> at Toji Cultural Centre, South Korea, 2013 (Writer-in-Residence)\n* Sangam House Fellow<ref>[http://www.sangamhouse.org/rajat-chaudhuri/ Sangam House Fellow]</ref> 2010 at Nrityagram, Bangalore, India\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Calcutta Nigts'' (2020) {{ISBN|9789389136456}}\n* ''The Butterfly Effect'' (2018) {{ISBN|9789386906526}}\n* ''The Best Asian Speculative Fiction (Edited)'' (2018) {{ISBN|9789811185281}}\n* ''Amber Dusk'' (2007) {{ISBN|978-8184430080}}\n* Short fiction in ''Eclectica''<ref>[http://www.eclectica.org/v14n3/chaudhuri.html (Vol 14, No 3)]</ref>\n* ''Hotel Calcutta'' (2013) {{ISBN|9789381523735}}\n* ''Calculus'' (2013) {{ISBN|9789384002039}}\n* ''Water \u2013 What are our Rights to it?'' {{ISBN|8187222158}}\n* ''Green Advertisements \u2013 Are they Telling the Truth'' (co-author)  {{ISBN|8187222425}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.rajatchaudhuri.net/ Rajat Chaudhuri's official website]\n\n<!-- (Commenting this out as we don't collect huge lists of external links, but if someone wants to use them to improve the article or integrate them into the text as citations, that would be great.)\n*\t[http://www.outlookindia.com/people/3/Rajat-Chaudhuri/14832 Rajat Chaudhuri] at [http://www.outlookindia.com/ Outlook]\n*\t[http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/esplanade-chatter/ Rajat Chaudhuri at Times of India Blogs]\n*\t[http://ibnlive.in.com/byline/Rajat-Chaudhuri.html Rajat Chaudhuri] at [http://ibnlive.in.com/ CNN-IBN Live]\n*\t[http://epaper.telegraphindia.com/paper/3-21-30@10@2014-1001.html Rajat Chaudhuri] at [http://www.telegraphindia.com/ The Telegraph]\n*\t[http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/the-enchanted-word/rajat-chaudhuri-recalls-his-experience-at-writers-residencies/ Interview with Rajat Chaudhuri on Times of India blogs]\n*\t[https://web.archive.org/web/20141104124850/http://unboxedwriters.com/2013/03/a-storytellers-world/ Interview with novelist Anu Kumar on Unboxed Writers about his book Hotel Calcutta]\n*\t[http://kitaab.org/2013/10/06/rajat-chaudhuri-mathematics-and-literature-are-twins/#more-3016/ Interview with Rajat Chaudhuri on Kitaab (South Asian Writing)]\n*     [http://www.eclectica.org/v14n3/contributor_notes.html#chaudhuri Profile at Eclectica webzine]\n* \t[http://www.sunday-guardian.com/bookbeat/a-dazzling-wall-of-stories-in-calcutta Hotel Calcutta review at Sunday Guardian]\n*     [http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130329/jsp/opinion/story_15973179.jsp#.VFioJPmUflG Hotel Calcutta review at The Telegraph]\n*\t[http://infohawk.uiowa.edu/F/?local_base=uiowa&func=find-b&find_code=ISBN&request=8184430086 Amber Dusk at University of Iowa libraries]\n* \t[http://lib.soas.ac.uk/search/?searchscope=3&searchtype=i&searcharg=8184430086 Amber Dusk at University of London, SOAS library] -->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chaudhuri, Rajat}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Kolkata]]\n[[Category:English-language writers from India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian novelist and short story writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{orphan|date=February 2015}}\n\n'''Rajat Chaudhuri''' is an Indian novelist and short story writer. He is the author of the critically acclaimed works ''Hotel Calcutta'' (2013), a short story cycle; ''The Butterfly Effect'' (2018), the novel ''Amber Dusk'' (2007) and other books.<ref>\"[http://www.asianreviewofbooks.com/new/?ID=1517 Review of Hotel Calcutta at Asian Review of Books, 27 July 2013]\". Retrieved 20 September 2014.</ref><ref>\"[https://scroll.in/article/906022/how-horribly-wrong-can-experiments-in-science-go-this-novel-of-ideas-explores-the-possibilities Review of The Butterfly Effect in Scroll]\". Retrieved 10 May 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/23340549?uid=3738256&uid=2&uid=4&sid=21104469196841 Review of Amber Dusk, Indian Literature journal, Vol 52, No.3, Sahitya Akademi]\", Sahitya Akademi. Retrieved 20 September 2014.</ref> He is also a book reviewer and literary critic, reviewing for such publications as ''[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]]'', [[CNN-IBN]]Live, ''[[Indian Literature (journal)|Indian Literature]]'' (published by [[Sahitya Akademi]], India's National Academy of Letters) and ''The Asian Review of Books''.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nRajat Chaudhuri grew up and lives in [[Kolkata]]. He attended school at [[Ramakrishna Mission Vidyalaya, Narendrapur|Ramakrishna Mission Vidyalaya]] and studied Economics at [[University of Calcutta]]. \n\n==Career==\nHe is a bilingual writer writing in English and Bengali. His books include the novel ''Amber Dusk'' (2007), the short story cycle ''Hotel Calcutta'' (2013), and ''Calculus'' (2014), a collection of Bengali short stories. \n\nHe is the Charles Wallace Creative Writing Fellow (2014) of the University of Chichester, United Kingdom, Hawthornden Castle Fellow, Scotland, United Kingdom, and a past of Fellow of Sangam House International Writers\u2019 Residency (2010), India.<ref>\"[http://www.chi.ac.uk/department-english-and-creative-writing/charles-wallace-india-trust-fellowship-creative-writing Charles Wallace India Trust Fellowship in Creative Writing at University of Chichester] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104145324/http://www.chi.ac.uk/department-english-and-creative-writing/charles-wallace-india-trust-fellowship-creative-writing |date=4 November 2014 }}\". Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://webzineold.arko.or.kr/?MID=boardInfo&IDX=4&IDX2=900 Profile and report at Arts Council Korea (ARKO) webzine, Nov 2013]\". Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.sangamhouse.org/rajat-chaudhuri/ Profile at Sangam House]\". Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref> He is a Korean Arts Council-InKo sponsored resident writer (2013) of Toji Cultural Centre, which was set up by acclaimed Korean novelist [[Park Kyung-ni]].\n\nHis fiction, criticism and essays have appeared in publications including ''Indian Literature'' (Sahitya Akademi), ''Asian Review of Books'' (Hong Kong), ''American Book Review'' (University of Houston-Victoria),<ref>\" [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/american_book_review/toc/abr.36.6.html Chitpur Local and the Rip Van Winkles of Calcutta. Volume 36, Number 6, September/October 2015, pp. 7-23].\" DOI [http://10.1353/abr.2015.0117 10.1353/abr.2015.0117]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved 2 April 2016.</ref> ''Thresholds'' (University of Chichester),<ref>\"[http://blogs.chi.ac.uk/shortstoryforum/three-stories-about-love/ \"Three Stories of Love\", ''Thresholds'', University of Chichester, 2015]\". Retrieved December 2015</ref> ''Eclectica'', and ''Outlook magazine''.\n\nChaudhuri has been directly involved with environment and development related activism and has contributed to the United Nations Development Programme's Human Development Report.<ref>\"[http://hdr.undp.org/sites/default/files/reports/259/hdr_1998_en_complete_nostats.pdf UNDP Human Development Report 1998]\", United Nations Development Programme. Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref> He lobbies for and supports environment related causes. \n\nHe has worked for and nurtured development, environment and consumer rights groups, and has spoken about environment and sustainable consumption issues in venues within and outside the country. He has published books and monographs on such topics as the right to water, sustainable consumption, and green advertisements.<ref>\"[http://www.worldcat.org/title/water-what-are-our-rights-to-it/oclc/609012412 Water: What are our Rights to it?]\"  Water: What are our Rights to it? Retrieved 10 October 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.worldcat.org/title/green-advertisements-are-they-telling-the-truth/oclc/588502226 Green Advertisements \u2013 Are they Telling the Truth?]\" Green Advertisements \u2013 Are they Telling the Truth? Retrieved 10 October 2014.</ref> \n\nChaudhuri has also served as the developing country (Southern) coordinator on the United Nations [[Commission on Sustainable Development]] (UNCSD) NGO caucus for climate change and energy.<ref>\"[http://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/content/documents/1623MG%20guidelines.pdf Guidelines for Major Groups on CSD 9]\". Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref> He has appeared in environment, science fiction and international cultural meetings and communication fora like Escape Velocity organised by [[Museum of Science Fiction]] in Washington D.C., [[International Communication Association]] (ICA) events and other places speaking about biotechnology in fiction, sustainability narratives and allied issues while doing readings from his books.<ref>[https://escapevelocity2019.sched.com/speaker/rajat_chaudhuri.jumxyz98 Rajat Chaudhuri, Escape Velocity 2019]\", Retrieved 06 June 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.rajatchaudhuri.net/p/blog-page.html Rajat Chaudhuri, The Butterfly Effect]\", Retrieved 06 June 2019.</ref>    \n\n=== ''The Butterfly Effect'' ===\nAt the centre of a near-future, post-apocalyptic Darkland is the chaotic city of Calcutta. Here Captain Old, a retired policeman who is also a hired assassin receives news that could help unravel the roots of a scourge that has devastated the continent. But problems begin to pile up for him till his own life is at stake. In another narrative we find a group of Indian tourists disappearing in Korea and a detective arriving in Seoul to investigate. But soon the private eye is overwhelmed by incidents that is far beyond his ken as a crime investigator. \n\nMeanwhile in England there is a hotshot geneticist working away on a secret project which he believes could change the world. Each of these distinct but interconnected narratives, arranged in a Russian doll<ref>\"[https://scroll.in/article/892151/this-timely-novel-explores-a-dystopian-asian-future-the-result-of-interference-with-nature/ Book Ecerpt,Scroll.in]\", Retrieved 29 September 2018.</ref> structure, mingle with each other as we near the resolution of this work of speculative fiction which balances science, spirituality and a gentle way of life. This novel has been compared to [[Philip K. Dick]]'s [[Blade Runner]] (based on Dick's 1968 novel [[Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?]]) for its dystopian settings.<ref>\"[https://www-outlookindia-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.outlookindia.com/magazine/amp/books-calcutta-in-dark-sci/301138?usqp=mq331AQCCAE%3D&amp_js_v=0.1#aoh=15507883077220&csi=1&referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.outlookindia.com%2Fmagazine%2Fstory%2Fbooks-calcutta-in-dark-sci%2F301138/ Calcutta in Dark Sci in Outlook Magazine, February 2019]\", Retrieved 02 March 2019.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.consumingcyberpunk.com/blog/2019/1/7/chasing-the-moment-in-the-butterfly-effect/ Chasing the Moment in the Butterfly Effect, Consuming Cyberpunk, January 2019]\", Retrieved 27 February 2019.</ref> This book has been listed by Book Riot community as one of \"50 must-read novels about eco-disaster\".<ref>\"[https://bookriot.com/2019/04/22/novels-about-eco-disasters/ 50 Must Read Novels about Eco-Disaster, Book Riot, April 2019]\", Retrieved 06 June 2019.</ref>\n\n=== ''Calcutta Nights'' ===\nTranslated work of narrative nonfiction originally written in Bengali (titled Raater Kolkata) by author [[Hemendra Kumar Roy]] in the year 1923. Translated into English by Rajat Chaudhuri, Calcutta Nights is the real-life account of the night-time wanderings of author Hemendra Kumar Roy in the forbidden, dangerous and exciting places of the city of [[Calcutta]].<ref>\"[https://www.dailypioneer.com/2020/sunday-edition/babus--bordellos--and-gaslit-nights.html/ Babus, Bordellos, and Gaslit Nights, The Pioneer, 12 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref><ref>\"[https://scroll.in/article/948962/calcuttas-ladies-of-the-night-a-forgotten-bengali-classic-offers-a-glimpse-of-a-racy-lifestyle/ Calcutta\u2019s ladies of the night: A forgotten Bengali classic offers a glimpse of a racy lifestyle, Scroll.in, 07 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/book-reveals-kolkatas-best-kept-secrets/1720549/ Book reveals Kolkata\u2019s best kept secrets, Outlook, 29 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref> The chapters in the book cover the brothels of Calcutta's red-light district, the dens of hoodlums, the crematoriums, night-time theatres, beggars hovels, festive streets, the `white town' area of Esplanade, hotels among others. The book according to reports `reveals Calcutta's best kept secrets' and acts like a `guidebook to the dark dens of eeriness' of the city of Calcutta.<ref>\"[https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/book-reveals-kolkatas-best-kept-secrets/1720549/ Book reveals Kolkata\u2019s best kept secrets, Outlook, 29 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/2020/jan/19/from-the-written-world-books-to-look-out-for-in-2020-2091352.html/ From the written world: Books to look out for in 2020, The New Indian Express, 19 January 2020]\", Retrieved 24 February 2020.</ref>\n\n=== ''Hotel Calcutta'' ===\nAn old Calcutta hotel is under the threat of demolition from land sharks  who want to replace it with a shopping mall. At this time a monk appears and prophesies that the hotel can be saved if people tell stories within its four walls every day. Thus begins a chain of storytelling by guests and hotel staff which brings together  realistic and speculative storytelling traditions. The frame story of the hotel's possible demolition flows parallelly till in the final pages there is an unexpected resolution. This book has been mentioned by critics for its evocative descriptions and the magic of storytelling.<ref>\"[http://www.thethumbprintmag.com/the-magic-of-storytelling/ The Magic of Storytelling, Anu Kumar, The Thumb Print Magazine]\",  Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref>\n\n=== ''Amber Dusk'' ===\n''Amber Dusk'' is a cross-cultural novel set in Calcutta and Paris amidst the rapid economic changes of a newly liberalised India. The young Rishi, in love with the French photographer Valence, travels west for work. Meanwhile, his friend, the hard nosed Pedro Braganza, looking for the good life, is taking too many chances in Calcutta. \n\nWhile in Paris, Rishi gets drawn into a vortex of racism and sporadic violence unleashed on the city by a little known neo-Nazi white supremacist outfit. Pedro has been putting in place his get-rich-quick plans and the initial success goes to his head. Then something happens which puts the two friends on a collision course against each other. It will be difficult for both of them to come out of it unscathed.\n\nThe novel was welcomed by critics for exploring surrealistic themes and for its handling of cross-cultural themes.<ref>\"[http://archive.deccanherald.com/content/Feb32008/books2008020250107.asp Surreal Explored, Deccan Herald, 3rd Feb, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105234605/http://archive.deccanherald.com/content/Feb32008/books2008020250107.asp |date=2014-11-05 }}\", Retrieved 19 September 2014.</ref>\n\n=== ''The Best Asian Speculative Fiction'' ===\n\nAn edited anthology of speculative stories from all over Asia selected, edited and introduced by Rajat Chaudhuri, the book covers science fiction, fantasy, horror, weird and other sub-genres of speculative fiction from authors in more than a dozen Asian countries. \n\nThe book has been described as \"one of the most comprehensive speculative fiction collection from the continent.\"<ref>[https://www.singaporewritersfestival.com/nacswf/nacswf/programme-listing/free-events/The-Best-Asian-Short-Stories-2018.html Singapore Writers Festival] Retrieved 19 December 2018.</ref> The critic for The Telegraph describes this book of stories as being at \"the brink of a strange new world\" and as a \"necessary and successful conglomerate.\"<ref>[https://epaper.telegraphindia.com/imageview_266596_15412744_4_71_26-04-2019_15_i_1_sf.html The Telegraph, India] Retrieved 6 June 2019.</ref> The literary commentator Agnes S. K. Yeow  writing in Southeast Asian Review of English (SARE)<ref>[https://sare.um.edu.my/article/view/21090/10727 Yeow, Agnes S.K. (October 30, 2009). Book review in Southeast Asian Review of English (SARE), Universiti Malaya, Vol 56, Issue 2, 2019.] Accessed December 26, 2019.</ref> has described the book as `An important contribution to an ever-expanding and dynamic literary form'.\n\n=== ''Calculus'' ===\n''Calculus'' is a collection of short fiction written in Bengali. Set in the city of Calcutta and its outskirts these stories bring together characters like autorickshaw drivers who speak a dead language, tantric practitioners with secret agendas, occult detectives and more which finally portray hidden facets of the city and its people.  \n\nCritics have described the stories as postmodernist and magical, with one critic saying the book \"transports us to a symbolic plane of existence, perched between the possible and the impossible.\"<ref>[http://ekakmatra2013.blogspot.in/2016/02/blog-post.html Politics peley oboshyoi porben. (in Bengali) Book review of Calculus in Ekak Matra, February 2016.] Retrieved 6 March 2016.</ref>\n\n== Fellowships and awards ==\n* Hawthornden Fellow, Scotland, UK, 2015<ref>[http://kitaab.org/2015/07/24/demons-at-a-calcutta-playhouse-kitaab-review-of-the-firebird-by-saikat-majumdar/ Hawthornden Fellow, Scotland, UK, 2015]</ref>\n* Charles Wallace Creative Writing Fellow<ref>[http://www.britishcouncil.in/study-uk/scholarships/charles-wallace-trust/visiting-fellows Charles Wallace Creative Writing Fellow]</ref> at University of Chichester, United Kingdom, 2014\n* Arts Council Korea<ref>[http://webzineold.arko.or.kr/?MID=boardInfo&IDX=4&IDX2=900 Arts Council Korea]</ref> and InKo Fellow<ref>[http://www.inkocentre.org/Indian_writer_at_Writing_Residency.html InKo Fellow]</ref> at Toji Cultural Centre, South Korea, 2013 (Writer-in-Residence)\n* Sangam House Fellow<ref>[http://www.sangamhouse.org/rajat-chaudhuri/ Sangam House Fellow]</ref> 2010 at Nrityagram, Bangalore, India\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* ''Calcutta Nigts'' (2020) {{ISBN|9789389136456}}\n* ''The Butterfly Effect'' (2018) {{ISBN|9789386906526}}\n* ''The Best Asian Speculative Fiction (Edited)'' (2018) {{ISBN|9789811185281}}\n* ''Amber Dusk'' (2007) {{ISBN|978-8184430080}}\n* Short fiction in ''Eclectica''<ref>[http://www.eclectica.org/v14n3/chaudhuri.html (Vol 14, No 3)]</ref>\n* ''Hotel Calcutta'' (2013) {{ISBN|9789381523735}}\n* ''Calculus'' (2013) {{ISBN|9789384002039}}\n* ''Water \u2013 What are our Rights to it?'' {{ISBN|8187222158}}\n* ''Green Advertisements \u2013 Are they Telling the Truth'' (co-author)  {{ISBN|8187222425}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.rajatchaudhuri.net/ Rajat Chaudhuri's official website]\n\n<!-- (Commenting this out as we don't collect huge lists of external links, but if someone wants to use them to improve the article or integrate them into the text as citations, that would be great.)\n*\t[http://www.outlookindia.com/people/3/Rajat-Chaudhuri/14832 Rajat Chaudhuri] at [http://www.outlookindia.com/ Outlook]\n*\t[http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/esplanade-chatter/ Rajat Chaudhuri at Times of India Blogs]\n*\t[http://ibnlive.in.com/byline/Rajat-Chaudhuri.html Rajat Chaudhuri] at [http://ibnlive.in.com/ CNN-IBN Live]\n*\t[http://epaper.telegraphindia.com/paper/3-21-30@10@2014-1001.html Rajat Chaudhuri] at [http://www.telegraphindia.com/ The Telegraph]\n*\t[http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/the-enchanted-word/rajat-chaudhuri-recalls-his-experience-at-writers-residencies/ Interview with Rajat Chaudhuri on Times of India blogs]\n*\t[https://web.archive.org/web/20141104124850/http://unboxedwriters.com/2013/03/a-storytellers-world/ Interview with novelist Anu Kumar on Unboxed Writers about his book Hotel Calcutta]\n*\t[http://kitaab.org/2013/10/06/rajat-chaudhuri-mathematics-and-literature-are-twins/#more-3016/ Interview with Rajat Chaudhuri on Kitaab (South Asian Writing)]\n*     [http://www.eclectica.org/v14n3/contributor_notes.html#chaudhuri Profile at Eclectica webzine]\n* \t[http://www.sunday-guardian.com/bookbeat/a-dazzling-wall-of-stories-in-calcutta Hotel Calcutta review at Sunday Guardian]\n*     [http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130329/jsp/opinion/story_15973179.jsp#.VFioJPmUflG Hotel Calcutta review at The Telegraph]\n*\t[http://infohawk.uiowa.edu/F/?local_base=uiowa&func=find-b&find_code=ISBN&request=8184430086 Amber Dusk at University of Iowa libraries]\n* \t[http://lib.soas.ac.uk/search/?searchscope=3&searchtype=i&searcharg=8184430086 Amber Dusk at University of London, SOAS library] -->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chaudhuri, Rajat}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Kolkata]]\n[[Category:English-language writers from India]]\n", "name_user": "Crabandbee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCalcutta Nights", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rajat_Chaudhuri"}
{"title_page": "Jay Whitehead", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2010}}\n'''Jay Whitehead''' (born April 8, 1959) is an [[United States|American]] [[author]] and [[publisher]] most notable for publishing ''Corporate Responsibility Officer'' (CRO) magazine.<ref>[http://www.thecro.com www.thecro.com]</ref>\n\n==Writing and publishing career==\nWhitehead graduated from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]. \nHe co-founded ''The CRO Association''.<ref>[http://www.croassociation.org www.croassociation.org]</ref> He published ''Human Resources Outsourcing Today''<ref>[http://www.hrotoday.com www.hrotoday.com]</ref> and ''HRO Europe Magazines''.<ref>[http://www.hroeurope.com www.hroeurope.com]</ref> He co-founded ''The HRO Association''.<ref>[http://www.hroassociation.org www.hroassociation.org]</ref>\n\nHis magazine ''Corporate Responsibility Officer'' issues an annual list, The 100 Best Corporate Citizens,.<ref>[http://www.thecro.com/100best09 www.thecro.com/100best09]</ref> This effort was ranked by [[PR Week]]/[[Burson-Marsteller]] as the 3rd most influential corporate ranking in the nation.<ref>[http://goodcorporatecitizen.com http://goodcorporatecitizen.com]</ref> In 2009 Whitehead was named #73 on [[Ethisphere Magazine]]'s 100 Most Influential People in Business Ethics list.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ethisphere.com/2009s-100-most-influential-people-in-business-ethics/ |title=ethisphere.com |access-date=2009-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106134839/http://ethisphere.com/2009s-100-most-influential-people-in-business-ethics/ |archive-date=2010-01-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhitehead is co-author (with Amit Chatterjee) of the 2009 book ''The Post-Carbon Economy''.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_ss?url=search-alias%3Daps&field-keywords=the+post-carbon+economy&x=13&y=16 www.amazon.com]</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2012, Whitehead started serving as CEO of Charity Partners, Inc. and [[Tickets-for-Charity.com]].\n\n==Personal==\nWhitehead is an avid [[marathon]] runner.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100106134839/http://ethisphere.com/2009s-100-most-influential-people-in-business-ethics/] \u2014 [[Ethisphere Magazine]]'s 100 Most Influential People in Business Ethics List for 2009\n*[http://corporateecoforum.com/ecoinnovator/?p=4911] EcoInnovator's review of The Post-Carbon Economy book\n*[http://www.thecro.com] Corporate Responsibility Officer magazine's website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110724184550/http://www.managingautomation.com/maonline/magazine/read/view/DeepDive_Expert_QampA__Welcome_to_the_PostCarbon_Economy_27755833] Managing Automation magazine's interview with co-author of The Post-Carbon Economy\n*[http://bostonherald.com/business/business_markets/2013/02/charities_score_with_ticket_ite] Boston Herald features Jay Whitehead as CEO of Tickets-for-Charity.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitehead, Jay}}\n[[Category:Corporate governance in the United States]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=November 2010}}\n'''Jay Whitehead''' (born April 8, 1959) is an [[United States|American]] [[author]] and [[publisher]] most notable for publishing ''Corporate Responsibility Officer'' (CRO) magazine.<ref>[http://www.thecro.com www.thecro.com]</ref>\n\n==Writing and publishing career==\nWhitehead graduated from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]. \nHe co-founded ''The CRO Association''.<ref>[http://www.croassociation.org www.croassociation.org]</ref> He published ''Human Resources Outsourcing Today''<ref>[http://www.hrotoday.com www.hrotoday.com]</ref> and ''HRO Europe Magazines''.<ref>[http://www.hroeurope.com www.hroeurope.com]</ref> He co-founded ''The HRO Association''.<ref>[http://www.hroassociation.org www.hroassociation.org]</ref>\n\nHis magazine ''Corporate Responsibility Officer'' issues an annual list, The 100 Best Corporate Citizens,.<ref>[http://www.thecro.com/100best09 www.thecro.com/100best09]</ref> This effort was ranked by [[PR Week]]/[[Burson-Marsteller]] as the 3rd most influential corporate ranking in the nation.<ref>[http://goodcorporatecitizen.com http://goodcorporatecitizen.com]</ref> In 2009 Whitehead was named #73 on [[Ethisphere Magazine]]'s 100 Most Influential People in Business Ethics list.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ethisphere.com/2009s-100-most-influential-people-in-business-ethics/ |title=ethisphere.com |access-date=2009-12-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106134839/http://ethisphere.com/2009s-100-most-influential-people-in-business-ethics/ |archive-date=2010-01-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhitehead is co-author (with Amit Chatterjee) of the 2009 book ''The Post-Carbon Economy''.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_ss?url=search-alias%3Daps&field-keywords=the+post-carbon+economy&x=13&y=16 www.amazon.com]</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2012, Whitehead started serving as CEO of Charity Partners, Inc. and [[Tickets-for-Charity.com]].\n\n==Personal==\nWhitehead is an avid [[marathon]] runner.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100106134839/http://ethisphere.com/2009s-100-most-influential-people-in-business-ethics/] \u2014 [[Ethisphere Magazine]]'s 100 Most Influential People in Business Ethics List for 2009\n*[http://corporateecoforum.com/ecoinnovator/?p=4911] EcoInnovator's review of The Post-Carbon Economy book\n*[http://www.thecro.com] Corporate Responsibility Officer magazine's website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110724184550/http://www.managingautomation.com/maonline/magazine/read/view/DeepDive_Expert_QampA__Welcome_to_the_PostCarbon_Economy_27755833] Managing Automation magazine's interview with co-author of The Post-Carbon Economy\n*[http://bostonherald.com/business/business_markets/2013/02/charities_score_with_ticket_ite] Boston Herald features Jay Whitehead as CEO of Tickets-for-Charity.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitehead, Jay}}\n[[Category:Corporate governance in the United States]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Whitehead"}
{"title_page": "Morat (band)", "text_new": "{{short description|Colombian folk-pop Band}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Morat\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = Morat en concierto.jpg\n| landscape        = \n| alias            = Malta\n| origin           = [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Folk pop]]\n}}\n| years_active     = 2015\u2013present\n| label            = [[Universal Music Group]]\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.moratoficial.com/}}\n| current_members  = <!-- Alphabetical order, per last name. -->\n* Juan Pablo Isaza\n* Mart\u00edn Vargas\n* Sim\u00f3n Vargas\n* Juan Pablo Villamil\n| past_members     = * Alejandro Posada\n}}\n\n'''Morat''' is a Colombian band formed in the country's capital city, [[Bogot\u00e1]]. The band is formed by Juan Pablo Isaza (guitars and vocals), Juan Pablo Villamil (banjo and vocals) and the brothers Sim\u00f3n Vargas (bass and choruses) and Mart\u00edn Vargas (percussion and choirs). Previously, until the end of 2016, drummer Alejandro Posada had been in the band, but the percussionist had to leave the project, who was replaced by Mart\u00edn Vargas.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Formation ===\nThe members of Morat have known each other since they were five years old.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elconfidencial.com/cultura/2017-11-23/musica-morat-pelotazo-pop_1479418/ |title=Morat, el pelotazo que vuelve locas a tus hijas |first=V\u00edctor |last=Lenore |date=23 November 2017 |access-date=14 April 2019 |newspaper=[[El Confidencial]] |language=es |publisher=Titania Compa\u00f1\u00eda Editorial, S.L.}}</ref> They all studied together at the La Monta\u00f1a Gymnasium in Bogot\u00e1, and some of them at [[University of Los Andes (Colombia)|University of Los Andes]]. They started playing together several times and, when they finished their formation, they decided to create a band. Some of their musical influences are Joaqu\u00edn Sabina, Eric Clapton and Bacilos.\n\nThe band's original name was \"Malta\". The name was inspired by a pet owned by Isaza. They switched to \"Morat\" because it was the surname of an ancestor of Alejandro Posada, former member of the band. The name was also inspired by the farm where the band made their first rehearsals which was named \"La Morat\":<ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://us.hola.com/actualidad/2016062386665/morat-detalles/ |title=Morat, as\u00ed es la banda colombiana que ha puesto 'patas arriba' el verano |date=23 June 2016 |magazine=[[Hola!]] |language=es |access-date=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2014-2017: ''Sobre el amor y sus efectos secundarios'' ===\nMorat saw their first turning point when the singer [[Paulina Rubio]] showed interests in their composition \"Mi Nuevo Vicio\" and wanted them to turn it into a single.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/musica/20161004/41752187712/morat-paulina-rubio-entrevista.html|title=\u201cCedimos \u2018Mi nuevo vicio\u2019 a Paulina porque sab\u00edamos que har\u00edamos temas mejores\u201d|date=4 October 2016|publisher=La Vanguardia}}</ref> In 2015, \"[[Mi Nuevo Vicio]]\" was released under the collaboration of [[Paulina Rubio]] and Morat, achieving great success internationally. The single rose to No.12 on the Billboard Latin Pop Airplay chart, and reached No.1 in Spain.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7378272/morat-band-on-the-rise|title=Meet Morat, the Colombian Pop Band Who Hit the Charts With Paulina Rubio|publisher=Billboard|date=20 May 2016}}</ref> The single was also certified Platinum Record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telecinco.es/quetiempotanfeliz/actuaciones/Terelu-entrego-Platino-Paulina-Rubio_2_2006580078.html |title=Terelu entreg\u00f3 el disco de Platino a Paulina Rubio por sus ventas de \u2018Mi nuevo vicio\u2019 |date=20 June 2015 |access-date=14 April 2019 |work=[[Telecinco]] |publisher=[[Mediaset Espa\u00f1a]]}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 2015, they received another international success with the new single, \"C\u00f3mo te atreves\", reaching the peak position in [[iTunes]] and bringing them to fame in Spain. In June 2016, Morat released their first studio album ''[[Sobre el amor y sus efectos secundarios]]'' through [[Universal Music Group|Universal Music Spain]]. The album debuted No.1 in several Hispanic countries such as Colombia, Mexico or Spain. Within this album, Morat obtained 4x Platinum Record as well as a Latin Grammy award nomination for \"C\u00f3mo te atreves\", and Golden Record for \"Cu\u00e1nto me duele\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.europapress.es/andalucia/noticia-morat-presentara-disco-amor-efectos-secundarios-marzo-granada-20170130125437.html|title=Morat presentar\u00e1 su disco 'Sobre el amor y sus efectos secundarios' el 9 de marzo en Granada|publisher=[[Europa Press]]|date=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Morat produced the single \"[[Yo contigo, t\u00fa conmigo (The Gong Gong Song)|Yo Contigo, T\u00fa Conmigo]]\" in collaboration with [[\u00c1lvaro Soler]] as the theme music of [[Despicable Me 3]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rlm.es/2017/06/12/morat-y-alvaro-soler-ponen-musica-a-gru-3-mi-villano-favorito-a-la-venta-el-16-de-junio/|title=MORAT Y \u00c1LVARO SOLER PONEN M\u00daSICA A \u2018GRU 3. MI VILLANO FAVORITO\u2019, A LA VENTA EL 16 DE JUNIO|date=12 June 2017}}</ref>. The single peaked at No.9 on Billboard on August 19, 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/morat/chart-history/italy-digital-song-sales/song/1032342|title=Chart History Morat \"Yo Contigo, T\u00fa Conmigo\"}}</ref> and won the \"Song of the Year\" award in [[LOS40 Music Awards 2017]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://los40.com/los40/2017/11/14/videos/1510672836_079372.html|title=\u2018YO CONTIGO, T\u00da CONMIGO\u2019 EN DIRECTO EN LOS40 MUSIC AWARDS|publisher=Los40}}</ref>. This single was later included in the re-issue of ''Sobre el amor y sus efectos secundarios'', which also contains the acoustic version of \"C\u00f3mo te atreves\".\n\n=== 2017-2019: ''Balas perdidas'' ===\n\nIn 2018, Morat released their second studio album the single ''[[Balas perdidas]]''. The single \"Cuando nadie ve\" peaked at No.1 on Billboard on August 18, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/morat/chart-history/MPE|title=Chart History Morat|publisher=Billboard|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>, and the single \"No se va\", released on March 7, 2019, hit almost 2 million visits on Youtube in less than a week<ref>{{cite news|url=https://los40.com/los40/2019/03/11/videoclips/1552322418_638553.html|title=MORAT PRESENTAN EL VIDEOCLIP DE \u2018NO SE VA\u2019|date=11 March 2019}}</ref>.\n\nEquipped with these success, Morat kicked off their first-ever US tour titled \"Balas perdidas\" to promote their album in 2019, with first performance in San Francisco on April 4, 2019. The tour ended in Orlando on May 5, 2019, with performance in other cities such as Los Angeles, Chicago, and New York.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8505377/morat-balas-perdidas-tour-interview|title=Morat Ready to Bring Their Colombian Flavor to the U.S. With Balas Perdidas Tour|publisher=Billboard|date=2 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://seitrackus.com/portal/en/morat-inicia-su-tan-esperada-gira-balasperdidasus-tour/|title=Morat kicked off their \u201cBalas Perdidas US Tour\u201d|publisher=Seitrack US|date=5 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April, 2019, Morat released a song collaborated with [[Aitana (singer)|Aitana]] named \"[[Presiento]]\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/musica/20190414/461639511735/aitana-morat-presiento-proyecto-video-seo-ext.html |title=Aitana colabora con el grupo Morat en \u2018Presiento\u2019 |date=14 April 2019 |access-date=14 April 2019 |newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]] |language=es}}</ref>. This single received more than 600,000 streams in [[Spotify]] in its first 24 hours. After that period of time, \"Presiento\" became the song with the highest debut in Spain, with more than 230,000 streams there, beating [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]] and [[J Balvin]]'s 2019 track \"[[Con altura]]\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vinilonegro.com/2019/04/presiento-de-morat-y-aitana-mejor-debut-del-ano-en-spotify-espana/|title=\u2018Presiento\u2019 de Morat y Aitana, mejor debut del a\u00f1o en Spotify Espa\u00f1a|date=2019-04-13|website=Vinilo Negro|language=es}}</ref>. \"Presiento\" was later included in the re-issue of Balas perdidas, ''Balas perdidas (Edici\u00f3n especial)'', on May 10, 2019 together with three other songs<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elrescatemusical.com/morat-balas-perdidas-edicion-especial/|title=Morat presenta \u2018Balas perdidas: Edici\u00f3n especial\u2019|publisher=El Rescate Musical|author=Sandra P\u00e9rez Abad|date=10 May 2019}}</ref>. \n\nOn December 15, 2019, Morat ended their Spain tour with the last performance at the [[Palacio de Deportes de la Comunidad de Madrid|WiZink Center]] in Madrid. [[Antonio Jos\u00e9 S\u00e1nchez Mazuecos|Antonio Jos\u00e9]], [[Aitana (singer)|Aitana]], [[Cali y El Dandee]], and [[Camila Anastasia Gallardo Montalva|Cami]] were also invited to perform at this concert.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://okdiario.com/happyfm/morat-cierra-gira-balas-perdidas-madrid-anuncia-vuelta-2020-4939655|title=Morat cierra su gira \u2018Balas Perdidas\u2019 en Madrid y anuncia su vuelta en 2020|publisher=HappyFM|date=16 December 2019}}</ref> Up to this show, Morat has held more than 80 concerts in 13 different countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://los40.com/los40/2019/12/16/musica/1576464137_392759.html|title=MADRID SE RINDE ANTE MORAT EN SU \u00daLTIMA \u201cBALA PERDIDA\u201d|date=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019-present: Upcoming third album===\n\nOn December 13, 2019, Morat released a new song \"Enam\u00f3rate de alguien m\u00e1s\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://laverdadnoticias.com/espectaculos/Morat-presenta-su-nueva-musica-para-cerrar-el-ano-Enamorate-de-alguien-mas-20191216-0281.html|title=Morat presenta su nueva m\u00fasica para cerrar el a\u00f1o \"Enam\u00f3rate de alguien m\u00e1s\"|date=16 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Morat is going to start another tour titled \"Galer\u00eda Inesperada\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://prensaocesa.prowly.com/89170-morat-llega-al-auditorio-nacional-con-nueva-gira-galeria-inesperada-tour|title=Morat llega al Auditorio Nacional con nueva gira: Galer\u00eda Inesperada Tour|date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Members ==\n'''Current'''\n* Juan Pablo Isaza Pineros \u2013 guitar, voice and choirs.\n* Juan Pablo Villamil \u2013 banjo, voice and choirs.\n* Sim\u00f3n Vargas \u2013 bass guitar, voice and choirs.\n* Mart\u00edn Vargas \u2013 percussion, voice and choirs.\n\n'''Former'''\n\n* Alejandro Posada \u2013 percussion, voice and choirs\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected chart positions and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.75em;font-size:85%;\" |  [[Asociaci\u00f3n Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas|MEX]]<br><ref>Peak positions for albums in Mexico:\n* ''Balas perdidas'': {{cite web|url= http://amprofon.com.mx/es/pages/rankings/top-album.php|title=Top 100 M\u00e9xico - Los m\u00e1s vendidos (semana del 2 al 8 de noviembre, 2018) |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=Spanish |publisher=Asociaci\u00f3n Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas |archive-url=https://archive.org/details/Toplbum100Mxico-LosMsVendidosdel5Al11DeOctubre2018|archive-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.75em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|SPA]]<br><ref>Peak chart positions for studio albums in Spain:\n* ''Sobre el amor y sus efectos secundarios'': {{cite web | url=https://spanishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Morat&titel=Sobre+el+amor+y+sus+efectos+secundarios&cat=a | title=MORAT - SOBRE EL AMOR Y SUS EFECTOS SECUNDARIOS (ALBUM)| work=spanishcharts.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}\n* ''Balas perdidas'': {{cite web | url=https://spanishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Morat&titel=Balas+perdidas&cat=a | title=MORAT - BALAS PERDIDAS (ALBUM)| work=spanishcharts.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Sobre el amor y sus efectos secundarios]]''\n|\n* Released: 17 June 2016\n* Label: Universal Music Spain\n* Formats: CD, digital downloading\n| - || 5\n| \n* [[PROMUSICAE]]: Gold <ref>{{cite web|title=TOP 100 Albumes - Semana 22: del 25.05.2018 al 31.05.2018\n|url=https://www.spanish-charts.com/uploads/9/4/0/4/94049395/\u00c1lbumes_-_25-5-2018_a_31-5-2018.pdf|publisher=[[PROMUSICAE]]|accessdate=12 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* [[AMPROFON]]: Platinum <ref name=\"AMPROFON\">{{cite web|title=Certificaciones AMPROFON|url=https://amprofon.com.mx/es/pages/certificaciones.php|publisher=[[AMPROFON]]|accessdate=12 April 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Balas perdidas]]''\n|\n* Released: 26 October 2018\n* Label: Universal Music Spain\n* Formats: CD, digital downloading\n| 1 || 1\n| \n* [[AMPROFON]]: Platinum <ref name=\"AMPROFON\"/>\n|}\n\n=== Extended plays ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of extended plays with selected details\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18.7em;\" | Extended play details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Grabado en Madera''\n|\n* Released: 24 July 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/es/album/grabado-en-madera-ep/1444430909|title=Grabado En Madera - EP|accessdate=14 April 2020|website=[[Apple Music]]}}</ref>\n* Label: Universal Music Spain\n* Format: Digital downloading\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n\n=== As lead artist ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles as lead artist, with selected chart positions and certifications, showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\" | [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.75em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|SPA]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://spanishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Morat | title=Discography Morat| work=spanishcharts.com |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Cu\u00e1nto me duele\"\n| 2015\n| 53 \n| \n| rowspan=\"3\" | ''Sobre el amor y sus efectos secundarios''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Del estadio al cielo\"\n| 2016\n| \u2014 \n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Amor con hielo\"\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 2017\n| 50 \n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Antes de los 20\"\n| \u2014 \n| \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Para que nadie se entere\"\n| \u2014 \n| \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Antes de los veinte\"\n| \u2014 \n| \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Yo contigo, t\u00fa conmigo (The Gong Gong Song)|Yo Contigo, T\u00fa Conmigo]]\" <small>(with [[\u00c1lvaro Soler]])</small>\n| 18 \n| \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Una Y Otra Vez\" <small>(with Santiago Cruz)</small>\n| rowspan=\"7\" | 2018\n| \u2014 \n| \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Punto y aparte\"\n| \u2014 \n| \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"No Se Va\"\n| \u2014 \n| \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"El embrujo\" <small>(with [[Antonio Carmona]] & Josemi Carmona)</small>\n| \u2014 \n| \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Yo no merezco volver\"\n| 88 \n| 